messages.text: Abby writhes beneath the knife, trembling.
But before the goon can do anything—
STOP! Stop! I’ll give it to you! I’ll give you whatever you want!
Eduardo nods to the goon, signaling him to drop the knife.
Just tell me what you want to know.
I’ll tell you anything—just let Abby go.
Eduardo gives another signal, and the goons cut Abby’s ties.
But before she can walk free, the goon holds a knife to her neck.
We need assurance.
My back left pocket.
There’s the key to our apartment.
If you go in my bedroom, there’s a bookshelf with encyclopedias on it.
Behind the encyclopedia’s is my work laptop.
The password is amarcourt1.
Everything I know or have on him is on that computer.
Eduardo smirks, satisfied.
Untie them.
Back at the mansion, Ezra Mohammed and Jack continue their conversation.
So what do you say?
I don’t know, Jack. You do have a point.
I would love Jazz to marry a Lebanese man... and you do fit that bill.
Before they can continue, Jazz interrupts.
Are you out of your mind?!
Jazz—we were just saying—
You think I’m going to marry this creep?!
I would rather die a thousand deaths!
Now, Jazz. That’s a bit hyperbolic.
You know we’ve always gotten along well.
Jack reaches out to touch Jazz’s arm, but she recoils.
Get away from me!
The only man I want is Alexander, and I think something’s happened to him.
He’s not answering my texts, and something isn’t right.
Baba, I need your help finding him.
Jazz, stop wasting your time with peasants.
Why? So I can spend it on creeps like you?
Jasmine—enough.
I wouldn’t marry you if my life depended on it.
Right then, Eduardo and the goons burst in.
We got the intel on Holt.
Jack smiles a slimy, evil grin and looks straight at Jazz.
That can be arranged.
Seize them!
The goons swoop in, grabbing Jazz and Ezra.
What is this about?! Jack!
Let me go— stop it!
But the goons’ grasp is tight.
Jack’s face darkens. He gets right in Ezra’s face.
For twenty-five years, you’ve built this business off of my back.
You were just a spoiled rich boy who never had to work a day in his life.
You inherited your wealth—you didn’t earn it.
But me—I built this company into what it is today.
And now I have the intel on the one key investor that you’ve never been able to secure.
The board will undoubtedly vote to give this company to me.
You are nothing.
I’m claiming what is rightfully mine.
You’re sick!
Jacob Proust—I have known you since you were a boy.
You bring shame to your family.
Stop this nonsense and unhand us.
I’ve had enough of your elitist attitude, you ungrateful bastard!
Jack turns to Jazz.
You want to know the truth about your beloved Alexander?
“Alexander”—what nonsense.
“Alexander” is Alex. He’s not an heir to a fortune- he’s a lowly streetrat who I paid to help me.
I picked him off the street and planted him at Holt’s company.
And all of this information came right from him.
So in a way, your “Alexander” brought down your father—how fitting.
Take them away! There’s a new boss in town.
three hours later
Alex and Abby, defeated, walk back to their apartment.
On the upside, we get to go back to normal life.
That’s the upside?
I feel like I haven’t seen you in ages.
Come on—why don’t we go to the farmer’s market?
I don’t want to do that.
You’re not too good for me now, are you?
Mr. Corporate big shot?
She keeps trying to tease him, but it’s fruitless.
My corporate days are long gone.
That went out the window when Jack sabotaged my relationship with Milton.
And now I’ve given them everything on him.
Milton will never trust me again.
And without the job, I’m nothing.
That job was everything that made me Alexander.
Without it, I’m just Alex.
You’re acting like they’re two different people.
They were!
Alexander was wealthy and cultured and had a great family.
Alex is just an orphan trying to get by.
You want to know the only difference between Alex and Alexander?
Alexander was confident.
Alex looks at Abby, contemplating this.
Just then, Alex notices a car parked on the side of the road.
A familiar looking man sits on the hood eating M&M’s.
Richie!
Richie’s face floods with recognition and then concern.
Buddy— what happened to you?
Ah, it’s kind of a long story.
This is my friend Abby.
Nice to meet you.
Hop in—you look like you could both use a good meal. My treat.
The three get into Richie’s limo.
I see why you liked Alexander’s life—this is much better than the brown line.
Richie parks at a Wendy’s.
It’s not a four-star steakhouse.
But it’s the best soft-serve on this side of the Atlantic.
And they’re fast—I have to pick the boss up in an hour for his flight to Tokyo.
He’s always traveling.
It sounds amazing.
I wish I had Milton’s life. Then I could do whatever I want.
Richie laughs.
Don’t be so certain.
Why do you say that?
Milton has hundreds of people to answer to.
Hundreds of people who need his input, his insight, and his output.
A lot of them depend on the success of his company to feed their families.
That’s a lot of responsibility.
He can’t just do whatever he wants—he has to do what’s needed.
His life isn’t his own.
You need to appreciate your life more, kid.
YOU’RE the free one.
You can make choices that will change the course of your life.
You just need to know what it is you want.
This hits Alex like a bolt of lightning.
Richie—can we take this order to go?
There’s something I need to do.
